	<li id="comment-24824" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 reader microid-mailto+http:sha1:be21842fc2c8b43f4730daa1503a0cd566f4ba2c">

		
		<div class="comment-meta-data">

			<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<cite class="fn" title="http://www.fashionanswers.blopgspot.com"><a href="http://www.fashionanswers.blopgspot.com" title="Kathy Friend" class="url external nofollow">Kathy Friend</a></cite>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->

			<abbr class="comment-time" title="Sunday, April 19th, 2009, 10:45 am">
				April 19, 2009 at 10:45 am			</abbr> 

			<span class="comment-sep comment-sep-permalink separator">|</span> 
			<a class="permalink" href="http://blissfullydomestic.com/2008/how-clothes-should-fit/comment-page-1#comment-24824" title="Permalink to comment 24824">Permalink</a>

			
			 

			
		</div><!-- .comment-meta-data -->

		<div class="comment-text">
			<p>Hi Fiona,</p>
<p>The &#8220;smile&#8221; and the waist are 2 different fit points.  The smile refers to the fit in the hip &#8211; not the waist.  If pants are too tight in the hip, you will see a stretch in the hip area (crotch area), or a wrinkling&#8230;this shows that they are too small.  </p>
<p>Many times (I would say 80% of the time) I&#8217;ve seen pants that fit perfectly everywhere but in the waist &#8211; there is a gap at the back.  This is a simple alteration &#8211; or you can get a product called IsABelt that will help cinch that in.</p>
<p>Hope this helps!</p>
<p>-Kathy</p>
		</div><!-- .comment-text -->
</li><!-- .comment -->
